Ask HN: Wouldn't it be cool if Boston Dynamics and OpenAI joined forces
text:
So I just had this thought experiment: what if some company like Boston dynamics created a robot that acts very much like a human, added a voice interface like Siri but instead of piss poor Siri tech it was powered by Chatgpt instead.

Wouldn't that be like the science fiction we've been seeing childhood come to life.

I think the chat/interaction part is really right there, but unsure how far boston dynamics type tech is from the physical part. Their recent videos sure look very promising.

But just imagine having something like this around. What a game changing time we're living in!

Show HN: Next-gen spreadsheet GRID launches GPT-3 powered formula copilot
text:
Hi Hacker News, We at GRID (a spreadsheet SaaS based in Reykjavik, Iceland) just launched GRID 2.0 today.

GRID combines the power of spreadsheets and presentation/text editing software into one product. You can edit your spreadsheet, and create an interactive doc on top of it which is connected to the underlying spreadsheet data. In today's launch, we introduced our GPT-3 powered formula assistant that allows you to write out queries in natural language, and the assistant will suggest formulas, right there in the cell.

We would love to hear your thoughts and feedback.

We are live on Product Hunt: https://www.producthunt.com/posts/grid-2-0

Read more about the launch: https://grid.is/blog/launching-grid-2-0-the-magical-surface-...

Check out this blog our founder wrote about the various ways GPT could be leveraged for spreadsheets: https://medium.grid.is/gpt-3-and-spreadsheets-4808acfda30d

The disjointed world of software project management
text:
I've worked at software companies big and small for about a decade and the one common theme I see is they all can do a better job organizing information about the software they build and maintain.

Things like architecture diagrams (high/low level diagrams, UML diagrams etc.), UI flowcharts, documentation, metrics etc. are all scattered across various tools that all do that one thing very well. E.g. metrics are in Splunk, documents are probably in Confluence/G-Docs etc.

But it's hard to know how they all tie together unless you have it "hardcoded" in your head. E.g. you must know which dashboard in Splunk surfaces the metrics you're looking for, you must also know which document/runbook in Confluence has the relevant information on how to act on those metrics. And more often than not this documented information, if it exists at all, drifts from reality.

Worse yet, the need for this "hardcoded" information is precisely what makes onboarding new hires hard; it's my least favorite part of joining a new team.

At one of my previous employers, we created a "team page" on the internal wiki that aggregated the team members' directory links, listed the services we owned, included some basic documentation and embedded metrics via iframes. But even that didn't meet our needs fully.

Wondering what the HN community feels about this problem (is it even a problem?) and if someone's using a tool that solves this for them at some level.
